# Why do we write?

```java
root.left = insertIntoBST(root.left, val);
```

Instead of

```java
insertIntoBST(root.left, val);
```

The recursive call returns the **updated subtree**.

We must reconnect that updated subtree back to the current node.

Example:

Before insertion:

```text
    5
   /
 null
```

Insert `3`

Recursive call returns:

```text
3
```

Now connect it:

```java
root.left = returnedNode;
```

Result:

```text
    5
   /
  3
```

Without assigning it back to `root.left`, the newly created node would not become part of the tree.

