| ------------------------ | ----------------------------------- |
| Search for a value       | Find the correct insertion position |
| Stop when value is found | Stop when `null` is found           |
| Return the node          | Create a new node                   |
| No tree modification     | Tree is updated                     |

Both problems use the same BST traversal logic.

---

# Interview Tips

* A new node is **always inserted at a leaf position** (`null`).
* Never violate the BST property (`Left < Root < Right`).
* In recursion, always reconnect the updated subtree:

```java
root.left = insertIntoBST(root.left, val);
```

or

```java
root.right = insertIntoBST(root.right, val);
```

* Always return the current root after insertion.

---

# Memory Trick

```text
Target < Root
      ↓
Go Left

Target > Root
      ↓
Go Right

Reached null
      ↓
Create New Node
```

Think of this problem as **"Search until you find an empty place, then insert the new node."**
